##What will the end result of the new crown disease be? Will it become a global pandemic? Experts say viruses could co-exist with humans for years

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The battle "plague" has already arrived at the midfield, what now must spell is the strategy and the tactic. The trouble is, the enemy is still out there, and the human race is still in tatters. The only thing we know for sure is that, given the new coronavirus's ability to spread, we can't win a blitz.

Victory is human after all. We already know a lot about viruses, and one of the most important things is that as viruses spread over many generations, they become less and less virulent. By their evolutionary nature, the more virulent strains die off as their human hosts die, leaving the less virulent ones behind.

Of course, this is also the virus evolved advantages, only less toxic, it can get more host, in order to long-term reproduction. That's how most viruses end.

So far, the only infectious disease that humans have really eradicated is smallpox, which is the only disease that humans have eradicated. So what happens to the new coronaviruses? Will it eventually be wiped out by humans, or will it co-exist with humans for as long as the flu virus does, and become an infectious disease, perhaps even a global epidemic? What's next with the domestic epidemic?

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In the face of an unknown virus, people are more scared. (Source: New York Times)

Deeptech asked several academics to share their views on these issues. They are Cowling, Benjamin Joh, a professor at the public health of the University of Hong Kong, Xu Fujie, an epidemiologist and professor at the First Affiliated Hospital of Zhejiang University, and Yang Gonghuan, former deputy director of the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention, huang Yanzhong, senior research fellow for Global Health at the Council on Foreign Relations, and Chen Zhuo, associate professor in the Department of Health Policy and management at the University of Georgia.

Question 1: Will New coronavirus infection become a global epidemic?

GAOBEN: We are still trying to stop the spread of the new coronavirus, but it has proved difficult. If we can't control its spread, it will become an epidemic, at least until we develop a vaccine.

As the virus adapts to humans, it can be expected that the severity of the infection will decrease over time. It wouldn't be surprising if the virus, like other human coronaviruses, causes flu like diseases.

Typically, it takes years to develop an effective vaccine. Even if the emergency accelerates development, it will take up to 12 months.

Xu Fujie: It is a question of probability, and effective prevention and control measures will reduce this probability, so the probability is determined by the defense and control measures of various countries, including China. This probability is dynamic, China initially weak prevention and control, but later, to overcome more difficulties, but the possibility of control still exists.

The effects of drugs can be immediate, and by focusing our efforts on developing a blockbuster antiviral or antibody, we can solve problems of confidence and fear. On the other hand, small improvements, such as timely optimization through clinical data sharing and analysis, can also reduce the number of patient deaths, but the question is how to form a sharing and synergy, China and the international can do it. Vaccine Development is long-term, its role depends on the future trend of the epidemic, but the same mutual cooperation can shorten the development of vaccine time.

Huang Yanzhong: After several generations of transmission, the virus will gradually weaken. For example, the 2009 H1N1 influenza pandemic, which began circulating in April of that year, ended on August 10,2010, when the World Health Organization declared that the H1N1 influenza pandemic was over. This is a more "desirable" situation considering the short duration of the virus and the low mortality rate.

If it becomes an infectious disease like seasonal influenza, which means that humans will coexist with it, we will basically have a more objective assessment of its characteristics and risks. A vaccine will be developed, so you don't have to worry about it.

It is too early to tell whether the new coronavirus infection will become a global epidemic. Basically, the main threat right now is China.

The World Health Organization has a concept of "Global Health Security, " which today refers to acute public health emergencies that pose a threat to several countries. That definition distinguishes the flu, which now exists in both China and the United States, from the current new coronavirus. The latter is a global health and safety concern, although the death toll is much lower than the flu.

Yang Gonghuan: The SARS virus has not appeared for more than 10 years, but you can not say that it has been eliminated, because in fact, we do not know very well why the SARS virus disappeared, so it is difficult to give a very accurate statement now.

In fact, we know very little about the new coronavirus. Some people are infected with a new coronavirus, which may or may not be present, and we may not be aware of it. If a lot of people develop protective antibodies, then even if there is an infection, it doesn't necessarily get sick. If there were more of them, it wouldn't be so scary.

Research into the virus could lead to a vaccine that we could potentially live with for a long time.

In the grand scheme of things, the relationship between humans and microbes is like this, because viruses can not be destroyed. Smallpox is the only thing we've eliminated, so it's important to regulate human behavior.

Question 2: What role would you like the WHO team to play in helping China in the future?

Yang Gonghuan: Global effort needed to fight new coronavirus pneumonia. The World Health Organization (WHO) brings together experts from all over the world to come to China, which is expected to be helpful to our prevention and treatment work at all levels, such as science, epidemiology, diagnostic testing and clinical treatment.

Huang Yanzhong: now has not found the source of the virus, this is a very difficult problem. So I suggest that the WHO not only send public health officials, doctors, epidemiologist, but also virologists. Especially now when some people question the Wuhan Virus Laboratory, the truth needs to be clarified.

In addition, WHO experts can know first-hand how the epidemic is progressing, assess the effectiveness of preventive measures, and assess whether existing response strategies need to be adjusted.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A CT scan of the lung of a patient with suspected coronavirus infection. (Source: Reuters)

Question 3: WHO expert and Professor David Hyman, an epidemiologist at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, says stopping the epidemic depends on a country's public health strength. What do you think?

Xu Fujie: means and management, is to choose effective and appropriate measures, management is to implement these measures, to be implemented to a reasonable place, reasonable people and reasonable time. I agree with Hyman, but it's understandable that a particularly powerful infectious disease could overwhelm a region's ability to cope, given that we're protected from the worst flooding in a century and the worst flooding in 500 years, something like the capacity of Levees.

Chen Zhuo: I agree with Professor Hyman. Comprehensive National Strength, governance capacity and mobilization capacity are also important factors to contain the spread of the epidemic. Wuhan City closure is probably unprecedented in modern history, few countries can do it.

Huang Yanzhong: On the one hand, we can see that China's public health has really made great progress compared to SARS, especially in the equalization of public health. The State has invested a lot more in this area than before, and the hardware facilities have basically done a lot. China's 2014 assessment of "core surveillance and response capacity" against the IHR met more than 90 percent of the target, a requirement that most developing countries failed to meet. So you can imagine what it would be like for some of the countries that don't have the emergency response capacity.

But it's not just about the hardware, it's also about the people and the system, how to run the system. Sometimes when you don't report an outbreak, the system doesn't work, does it? It's part of the strength of public health.

On the other hand, such an outbreak of disease, especially when Wuhan decided to close the city on January 23, had become a very big crisis, that said, Wuhan's existing public system is no longer able to cope.

So in terms of strength, it depends on your ability to deal with a crisis of this magnitude, which is what we call crisis management, the ability to put resources together quickly to deal with a crisis.

The 2009 H1N1 and 2013 H7N9 epidemics seem to give us the illusion that China can really control these outbreaks. The new outbreak has exposed the fragility of the Emergency Response Mechanism.

It is a big challenge to make up for lost ground once the crisis is over.

I also suggested the creation of a public health force modeled after the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, which some conspiracy theorists later described as a biological or genetic weapon used against other countries.

Question 4: Has China overreacted to the new coronavirus outbreak?

GAOBEN: We still need information about the severity of the infection, because we know that some infections can be very mild and others can be fatal. The available evidence suggests that, on average, coronavirus infections are much more severe than influenza virus infections. Therefore, efforts should be made to control its spread.

Question 5: Some people believe that Singapore should focus on the treatment of seriously ill patients and that the social and economic costs of containment strategies are unaffordable. How to go down according to local conditions?

Chen Zhuo: At present, there are still some uncertainties about the understanding of NCP. If the cure is really close to the magnitude of the flu, perhaps we can adjust our strategy, otherwise the economic costs will be too great.

Huang Yanzhong: I think the Singapore approach is quite sensible. That's because it actually learned the lesson of 2009, when Europe and the United States largely followed the advice of the World Health Organization and adjusted their strategies to stop or reduce losses.

Of course, we have to adapt to local conditions. For China, containment is still the way to go. At the same time to continue to track the death rate of new coronavirus, the daily increase in cases, assess the situation, timely adjustment.
